        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">CD had finished checking the proof-sheets of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1967.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi> 2d ed.</ref> (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9702.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to J. V. Carus, 30 October 1874</ref> and n. 1). The second edition was published in one volume in November 1874 (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9717.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from R. F. Cooke, 12 November 1874</ref> and n. 4).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">John Murray was the publisher of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1967.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi> 2d ed.</ref>, which contained three new woodcuts (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9388.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to John Murray, 4 April 1874</ref> and n. 4). <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_135.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">D. Appleton &amp; Co</ref>. published the second edition of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1966.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi></ref> in New York in 1875 (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1969.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi> 2d US ed.</ref>), using Murray’s stereotype plates (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2661.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Freeman 1977</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4097.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Insectivorous plants</hi></ref> was published by Murray in London on 2 July 1875; <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_135.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">D. Appleton &amp; Co</ref>. published the work in New York in 1875 (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4098.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Insectivorous plants</hi> US ed.</ref>), using Murray’s stereotype plates. See <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2661.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Freeman 1977</ref>. The recent popular literature to which CD refers might have included the articles ‘The carnivorous habits of certain plants’ and ‘The butterwort a carnivorous plant’ in <hi rend="italic">Hardwicke’s Science Gossip</hi> (1874): 230–3 and 235, and in America, the notice in <hi rend="italic">Scientific American</hi>, 4 April 1874, in which, under the heading ‘Carnivorous plants’, an account was given of <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4796.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Mary Treat’s</ref> publication on the sundew in <hi rend="italic">American Naturalist</hi> (Treat 1873).</note>
        </div>        
            
